The healthcare insurance industry continues to be one of the least competitive and least transparent industries in the entire nation. That’s because for over 70 years health insurers have enjoyed a special legal exemption from anti-trust laws resulting in less competition and higher healthcare costs for every single American family. By restoring federal anti-trust laws to the business of health insurance, my legislation that I introduced this week represents a critical first step to establishing the proper foundation for a competitive and consumer-driven health insurance marketplace. Hospitals, doctors and most importantly, patients benefit when health insurers compete to provide quality coverage. Ending this special-interest exemption is an integral piece of any Obamacare repeal effort and is the only reform that will actually rein in insurance company practices, increase competition and lower prices for consumers. Did you hear about it yesterday? It may not seem like a big victory to some, but Arizonans showed the nation how to fight and win against big government overreach. When the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service tried to stop Rainbow Trout stocking at the Willow Beach Fish Hatchery back in 2013, Arizonans fought back to stop this harmful action. Nearly 1,700 jobs in Mohave County and close to $75 million in economic output associated with the Willow Beach Hatchery were at stake. Due to constant vigilance and perseverance by many local leaders, we were able to stop the Fish and Wildlife Service. Yesterday, Rainbow Trout stocking returned once again at Willow Beach. This should inspire all Americans to remember that when ‘we the people’ stand together and take bold action against big government overreach, we can accomplish anything.

Right now, the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals is hearing oral arguments for President Trump’s Executive Order on temporarily suspending refugees and immigration from terrorist strongholds. Here are the facts: six of the last seven presidents have relied on the same executive powers Trump is using to keep certain groups of foreigners out of the United States. The Rule of Law clearly spells out those executive powers: 8 U.S.C. 1182(f): “Whenever the president finds that the entry of any aliens or of any class of aliens into the United States would be detrimental to the interests of the United States, he may by proclamation, and for such period as he shall deem necessary, suspend the entry of all aliens or any class of aliens as immigrants or nonimmigrants, or impose on the entry of aliens any restrictions he may deem to be appropriate.”

As a dentist impersonating a politician, I am going to tell Arizonans the truth about the updated version of the AHCA: This bill is NOT a full repeal, I repeat NOT a full repeal of Obamacare. However, after working alongside my colleagues in the House Freedom Caucus, we have been able to secure Conservative, time-tested changes to the original version of the AHCA. These changes will immediately eliminate Obamacare taxes, lower health insurance premiums, offer more choices for Arizonans and begins the process of rebuilding a patient-centered market.   Millions of Americans are drowning right now under the tidal wave of Obamacare regulations and mandates that have destroyed our entire healthcare system. The American Health Care Act is a life raft to those suffering and represents a down payment towards a true market-based solution. Additionally, the AHCA preserves protections for all Americans with pre-existing conditions and gives states the control needed to lower premiums, provide increased patient-centered choices and stabilize the insurance market.  While I will never stop fighting for a full repeal and replacement of Obamacare, the revised AHCA finally opens the door to free-market solutions that empowers states and individuals to have more control over health care decisions.

The National Park Service has been twiddling their thumbs for more than three years trying to develop a plan to address the ‘beefalo’ population in the Park. Today’s proposal was supposed to be published last summer. Unfortunately, the NPS has continuously pushed out half-cocked and costly management suggestions a day late and more than a few dollars short, failing to reduce the herd to sustainable levels and protect the Park from utter devastation.  After years of badgering, the NPS has finally warmed up to our proposal to put Arizona hunters to work and allow these skilled volunteers to keep the meat. While this is encouraging, the plan announced today is far from perfect. Legislation is still likely necessary as this proposal fails to provide a long-term management plan, creates a new 1:1 sex ratio goal to encourage future breeding, provides too much flexibility for the NPS to scrap lethal culling, and fails to allow skilled volunteers to keep the entire bison.  The picture on the left was taken in 2010 when there was no bison use in this particular pond. The picture on the right was taken in 2014 after high bison use.

The White House is looking for Fall Interns!  Get more info here and be sure to submit your application before 11:59 p.m. on June 16, 2017 → https://www.whitehouse.gov/participate/internships/apply  The Fall 2017 White House Internship Program application is now open.    The application portal will remain open until 11:59PM EDT on June 16, 2017.  Any applications received after the deadline will not be considered.     The Fall 2017 White House Internship Program term runs from September 6 to December 8, 2017.  All applicants must be at least 18 years of age by the Internship Program start date, and must be able to commit to the full internship term to be eligible.  Additionally, applicants must be U.S. citizens and meet at least one of the following criteria to apply:  - Are currently enrolled in an undergraduate or graduate degree program at a college, community college, or university (two-to-four year institution).  - Have graduated from an undergraduate or graduate degree program at a college, community college, or university (two-to-four year institution) no more than two years before the internship program start date.  - Are a veteran of the United States Armed Forces who possesses a high school diploma or its equivalent and has served on active duty—for any length of time—in the two years preceding the internship program start date.  The White House Internship Program is highly competitive.  Applicants are selected based on their demonstrated commitment to public service, leadership in the community, and commitment to the Trump Administration.  Questions about the White House Internship Program application can be directed to intern_application@who.eop.gov. More information, including details about placement in the White House Internship Program and frequently asked questions can be found on the White House website.

Today I introduced H.R. 2630, which would authorize the Secretary of the Interior to convey land Bureau of Land Management (BLM) to La Paz County, Arizona, in order to create economic development opportunities and facilitate renewable electricity generation for the Western United States.  My statement here: “I have long been an advocate of a true all-of-the-above energy strategy, and solar power is an integral part of a diverse, market-based energy mix. This bill will allow La Paz County to take advantage of one of their best assets, sunshine.”  “Because the immense federal footprint in the County leaves only roughly six percent of land available for taxable use, a land transfer is necessary for the County to secure enough space for this type of development. H.R. 2630 allows the County to secure title to 8,800 acres from the BLM for fair market value. The County can put this otherwise under-utilized land to more effective use by partnering with private renewable energy developers to create good-paying local jobs and build a diverse tax base to support basic public services. Supervisor Irwin and the County have done amazing work in helping craft this commonsense legislation.”  You can read my full release here → gosar.house.gov/press-release/rep-gosar-introduces-land-exchange-bill-foster-economic-development-and-job-creation

The #GosarReport: After chatting with 21 energetic students from Bullhead Middle School, I spoke with my former colleague Secretary Ryan Zinke at the House Committee on Natural Resources hearing. I'm encouraged to see he's running a right ship over at the Department of the Interior, and I have full confidence in his capabilities. The current regulatory process for constructing new surface water storage is a bureaucratic maze that requires numerous permits and approvals from a multitude of different federal, state and local agencies.  Conflicting mandates continue to cause unnecessary delays, kill jobs and result in us failing to capture precious water supplies.   Ranchers, agricultural and municipal water providers and other stakeholders in the West need a clear process without the bureaucracy.  H.R. 1654 establishes such a process by creating a “one-stop” permitting shop and requiring BOR to implement a coordinated regulatory structure for reviewing  projects and permits, coordinating agency reviews and consolidating important data.

The Doctor Is In:   I was proud to vote for long overdue tort reform.  I voted for H.R. 1215, which will go a long way to tackling frivolous medical malpractice suits, limiting out of control damage awards, and most importantly, take away the problem of “defensive medicine.”   Defensive medicine is where doctors order tests and sometimes do procedures not because they really think it is medically necessary, but because they are afraid of being sued if they don’t “do everything.”      It was a close vote, 218-210, as the trial lawyers fought this tooth and nail.  My hope is that this law will start to reform this practice, which costs taxpayers billions of dollars.

Today the House will vote on HR 3004, referred to as Kate’s Law.  Kate Steinle was a vibrant 32-year-old happily living her life in San Francisco. Two years ago,  Kate was murdered by Juan Francisco Lopez-Sanchez, an illegal immigrant who was roaming free despite his seven felony convictions.  He was deported five times, but simply walked back across our open border.  Let me repeat that for you. He was deported on five separate occasions and was still allowed to find sanctuary in San Francisco. It really is as ludicrous as it sounds, and you know who you can thank for that? The left.  Democrats in this country talk about how inspirational illegal immigration is, coining them as “dreamers,” but we know the truth. Criminals, sex traffickers, drug cartels, terrorists and others cross our borders illegally to commit crimes, use our health care, take our jobs and threaten our citizens. All because the Obama Administration allowed it to happen by diminishing the Rule of Law in the United States. But we must not quit fighting the good fight. The Rule of Law is the only thing that protects freedom from terror, and we must stop at nothing to maintain it.  We’ve had enough. Obama’s open borders have wreaked havoc all over this great nation. Taking back our country from an illegal invasion of criminals starts now.   Kate’s Law will increase the penalties that may be imposed on criminal aliens convicted of illegal reentry, deterring reentry and keeping criminal aliens off our streets.  San Francisco calls itself a sanctuary city, but giving sanctuary to criminals, rapists and murderers is simply harboring fugitives and endangering the lives of real Americans.  In Arizona, Grant Ronnebeck was shot and killed by an illegal immigrant from Mexico, Apolinar Altamirano, while Grant was working his shift at a QT Market in Mesa.  Grant’s young life was taken needlessly by a criminal who never should have been in our country.    We must not forget those sent to their graves by people who had no right to be here.

3...2...1... The #CongressmansCountdown.  This week, a number of bills will be going to the floor for debate and a vote.  The majority of these bills deal with veterans, small business, and national defense.  I am a strong supporter of increasing our defenses nationwide, supporting small business, and, as always, giving our veterans the help they need when they need it most.   While strengthening our nation’s defense capabilities is critical, working within our fiscal means is equally important.  That’s why I’ve offered two amendments that will block an onerous Obama-era carbon rule and military amnesty for illegals. Funding bad programs not only wastes national resources, it wastes taxpayers’ money.  Last week, the House was informed that we would be discussing and voting on HR 3219, the Make America Secure Appropriations (MASA) Act.  This appropriations bill combines the funding language from the Military Construction and Veterans Affairs Appropriations, Dept. of Defense Appropriations, Energy & Water Appropriations and Legislative Branch Appropriations bills passed out of committee.  I will be reviewing the bill in its entirety, making decisions on whether it represents a fiscally sound approach.  As I mentioned earlier, I will be offering two amendments to this bill.    We must do everything we can to support our veterans and our troops, providing them with the tools they need to be successful.  And that's the #CongressmansCountdown.

Puerto Ricans are Americans, and they are facing grave danger in the weeks ahead.  On September 6, 2017, Puerto Rico was hit by Hurricane Irma, which damaged the island’s energy infrastructure, but escaped the worst. Then two weeks later, on September 20th, the island was devastated by Hurricane Maria resulting in:   • Loss of Life: 16 confirmed fatalities to date, a figure that unfortunately is likely to increase • Destruction of Property: According to Moody’s initial estimates go from $45 to $95 billion  • Energy: 1.57 million or 95% customers without electricity • Water: 44% of population without running water and structural failure at a dam with 11-billion-gallon water reservoir • Food Security: People stranded in the rural areas are potentially running out of food. 8 days into the crisis without the ability to refrigerate or cook has left many hungry and scared • Hospitals: 59 of 69 hospitals operational with unknown status and running on back-up generators that could run out of fuel at any time • Health Conditions: Many ambulatory dialysis patients and other critical care patients are in dire need of hospital care. Medical supplies are running critically low. • Telecommunications: 71.5% of cell sites are out of service • Transportation: Severe damage to 18 bridges and 6 highways; sections of 11 roads closed and only 3 major routes cleared of debris • Air & Maritime Ports: The San Juan International Airport has lost 6 of its 7 radars, forcing use of visual flight rules (VFR), which commercial airlines refrain from flying under due to insurance reasons. Many other maritime ports and airports are closed. The ones open are operating on restricted basis solely for military and hurricane relief.

For too long, inefficiencies and redundant requirements imposed by the federal government have discouraged oil and gas production on federal land, leading to duplicative environmental reviews and unnecessary permitting delays. This has led to a boom in development on state and private lands and a loss of state and federal revenues due to permitting backlogs.  The states have developed extensive regulatory frameworks for permitting oil and gas development on state lands. Energy-rich states not only do the work the BLM does, but do it more effectively, efficiently, and with less cost.  The legislation seeks to facilitate responsible onshore energy production on federal lands and promote economic prosperity in energy producing states in the West and in Alaska.
